- Saunders extraction candidates
    - format: per candidate, list chapter, location, paraphrase, situation, outcome
    - outcomes: → promoted to <slug>, → folded into <slug>, → dropped because <reason>

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: lines 243, 247
    - paraphrase: after finishing a story, collect honest felt reactions and locate each one at a specific spot on the page, refusing literary jargon
    - situation: you have just finished reading a story and want to learn from it (as reader or writer) without skipping the diagnostic data your own reactions provide
    - outcome: → promoted to the-basic-drill

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: line 241
    - paraphrase: when discussing or evaluating a story, shift the question from interpretive (what does X mean, what is X a metaphor for) to strategic (what is X doing for the reader, why do we need X)
    - situation: you are critiquing, teaching, revising, or workshopping a story and risk producing an interpretation that says nothing about how the story actually works
    - outcome: → promoted to ask-strategic-not-interpretive

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: line 271
    - paraphrase: judge a craft model, theory, or slogan by whether it is helping you reach the desired state of mind, not by whether it is correct (finger pointing at the moon, criterion: is it helping)
    - situation: you encounter a piece of writing advice, theory, or model and have to decide whether to adopt it, debate it, or discard it
    - outcome: → promoted to is-it-helping

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: lines 193, 197
    - paraphrase: keep a small set of touchstone stories as your high bar against which to measure your own work
    - situation: a writer wants an external standard for their own work
    - outcome: → dropped because the chapter mentions this in passing as autobiographical practice, with no concrete action, no observable signal, and no failure mode that distinguishes it from generic advice

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - location: line 251
    - paraphrase: treat reading as workbook work, with intent to go deeper than a first read allows
    - situation: a reader wants more than a casual encounter with a story
    - outcome: → folded into the-basic-drill (the drill itself is the "deeper than first read" mechanism Saunders is naming)

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 329-368, 735-748 (the explicit three-question protocol, repeated)
    - paraphrase: at a chosen pause in a story-in-progress, answer three specific questions about reader-state (what do you know, what are you curious about, where do you think it's headed) and treat the answers as the data the rest of the story must use
    - situation: you are mid-read of a story, mid-revision of a draft, or trying to learn how a story is working on you, and you want to make the moment-by-moment effects visible
    - outcome: → promoted to page-break-diagnostic

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 569-595 (explicit procedure with iterative refinement of summary)
    - paraphrase: produce a one-sentence "Hollywood version" of what the story appears to want to be, then iteratively adjust toward greater specificity, treating each refinement as artillery fire
    - situation: a workshop, critique session, or revision pass where the group is about to start suggesting changes before agreeing what the story is trying to do
    - outcome: → promoted to hollywood-version

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 964-973 (named principle, tested against the teahouse scene)
    - paraphrase: every structural unit of a story must (1) be entertaining in its own right and (2) advance the story in a non-trivial way; test each scene against both
    - situation: revising or critiquing a draft, encountering a scene whose presence you suspect but can't justify
    - outcome: → promoted to cornfeld-principle

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 822-855 (Hanov removed; "ritual banality avoidance" named); lines 841-845 ("push the new bead to the knot")
    - paraphrase: identify the obvious or expected first-order resolution your story is gesturing toward, then deliberately remove that option to force the story past its original plane of conception
    - situation: drafting or revising and noticing that the story is heading toward the satisfying-but-predictable resolution your reader has already imagined
    - outcome: → promoted to ritual-banality-avoidance

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 711-723 (worsening road vs. improving road); lines 944-952 (rough teahouse vs. cheerful teahouse)
    - paraphrase: when you suspect a craft choice is working but can't say why, write or imagine the inverted version of the same element and hold the two side by side until the difference becomes nameable
    - situation: revising, teaching, or trying to learn from a sentence/description/scene whose effect you feel but can't articulate
    - outcome: → promoted to two-version-comparison

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 415-434 (specification through ruling out); lines 916-924 (Marya's specification continues at the teahouse)
    - paraphrase: when introducing or developing a character, ask "which particular person is this?" and answer with facts that rule out clichéd alternatives, narrowing the path until meaningful action becomes possible
    - situation: drafting a story whose character feels generic or whose plot won't move because the character lacks traction
    - outcome: → promoted to increasing-specification

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 1130-1152 (truncate "In the Cart" and ask "Is it story yet?")
    - paraphrase: when judging whether a story is finished or what its ending is doing, experimentally cut the last section, read up to the cut, and observe what feels missing
    - situation: revising your own draft, or studying another story, and trying to isolate what the ending is supplying
    - outcome: → promoted to truncation-test

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 305-316, 368-378 ("expectation/resolution moments," juggler/bowling pins, curiosity-as-caring)
    - paraphrase: read each line as creating expectations the next must satisfy or complicate; track which "pins" are in the air
    - situation: any close reading
    - outcome: → folded into the-page-break-diagnostic (the procedural form Saunders gives this idea is the three-question protocol; the bowling pins are vocabulary for what the protocol surfaces)

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 1068-1082 (variation in Semyon's gossip beats; against stasis)
    - paraphrase: when a character or pattern recurs, alter at least one parameter so the second occurrence is not a static repeat of the first
    - situation: drafting and noticing a beat is about to repeat itself
    - outcome: → dropped because the procedural form is too vague (action: "vary it"), with no concrete signal that distinguishes good variation from random change; the underlying caution is captured by increasing-specification (don't let a character stay static)

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 627-633 (Hanov as warm-but-clueless; broad type cross-painted with contradictory info)
    - paraphrase: when introducing a character of a recognizable type, set up the type, then complicate it with a contradictory trait to produce three-dimensionality
    - situation: drafting a character whose type the reader will pattern-match
    - outcome: → folded into increasing-specification (cross-painting is one technique within the larger move of ruling out clichéd possibilities)

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 1331-1336 (motorcycle/sidecar metaphor for reader-writer closeness)
    - paraphrase: keep emotional distance between reader and protagonist small enough that the reader follows the character into whatever happens
    - situation: drafting, especially endings that ask the reader to absorb a difficult turn
    - outcome: → dropped because the chapter offers it as an evocative model, not a procedure; the action is too vague (no concrete way to measure or control "distance"); the closest concrete moves are already captured by increasing-specification and the page-break diagnostic

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - location: lines 497-512 (structure as call-and-response, story raises questions and answers them)
    - paraphrase: think of structure as the organizational scheme by which a story answers the questions it has caused its reader to ask
    - situation: analyzing or revising a story's overall shape
    - outcome: → folded into the-page-break-diagnostic (the questions a story has caused the reader to ask ARE what the diagnostic surfaces; the answer to "what is structure?" reduces to "the call-and-response between questions surfaced page by page and what the story does next")

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: lines 1355-1359 (Cat in the Rain classroom procedure: cut the story into 200-word "pages," ask the three questions per page, then truncate near the end and ask "Is it story yet?")
    - paraphrase: a teacher's recipe for running the page-at-a-time exercise on a fresh story by physically cutting it into pages
    - situation: a teacher running the exercise on a new short story in a class period
    - outcome: → folded into page-break-diagnostic and truncation-test (this is a packaging of the same two procedures applied to a different story; no new procedural content)

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: lines 1369-1377 ("a story is a series of incremental pulses... criticism is just (1) noticing ourselves responding moment by moment and (2) getting better at articulating that response")
    - paraphrase: a one-paragraph restatement of the line-by-line ethos: criticism is reaction-noticing plus reaction-articulating
    - situation: a reader who has finished a story and wants to learn from it
    - outcome: → folded into the-basic-drill (this is exactly the basic drill restated; "incremental pulses" overlaps with page-break-diagnostic; no novel procedure)

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: lines 1375-1377 (Hemingway's "built-in, shockproof, shit detector"; the deep, honest part of the mind reacts and that part is what reading and writing refine)
    - paraphrase: trust the deep honest reaction of the mind as a quality detector; reading and writing refine that faculty
    - situation: any reader/writer judging quality
    - outcome: → folded into the-basic-drill (this is a vivid name for the same diagnostic stance: any honest reaction is valid data; the move is unchanged)

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: lines 1387-1401 (Bicycle Thieves sequence audit: trees, the truck of fans, the wallet check, the loving couple in the background; "an artist takes responsibility for every single thing")
    - paraphrase: audit a composed unit (paragraph, scene, frame) element by element, asking what each one is doing for the reader; every element must have either a stated function or an explicit decision to keep it as atmosphere
    - situation: revising a unit where you suspect some details are there by default rather than by intent
    - outcome: → promoted to take-responsibility-for-every-element

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - location: line 1401 ("that's what an artist does: takes responsibility")
    - paraphrase: the disposition of taking responsibility for every choice in the work
    - situation: the artist's general stance toward their work
    - outcome: → folded into take-responsibility-for-every-element (this is the disposition the audit procedure operationalizes; not a separate move)

- Chapter 5: The Singers (Turgenev source story)
    - location: lines 1407-1635 (entire chapter)
    - paraphrase: no candidates. The chapter is Turgenev's story as Saunders presents it, with no Saunders commentary. Notable structural moves are visible (extended village/character portraits inserted between contest buildup and the contest itself; Yashka's transcendent song followed by a deflationary drunken-aftermath scene; narrator's choice to exit at the peak; the closing fade of the "Antropka" call across the valley) but none of these can be promoted to a skill from the story alone without leaning on Chapter 6's forthcoming commentary, which is out of scope for this pass.
    - situation: not applicable
    - outcome: → none promoted; the story is data the next chapter will use to teach moves about narrative structure and "the heart of the story"

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1656-1666 (TICHN cart, transactional reading state, "create a pattern of excesses and convert them into virtues")
    - paraphrase: while reading or revising, log non-normative features (presentational excesses) the writer is asking the reader to tolerate, then track whether the rest of the work redeems each one
    - situation: reading a story whose surface contains conspicuous oddities, or revising a draft where you want to tell which excesses are doing work and which are unredeemed
    - outcome: → promoted to track-non-normative-excesses

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1676-1694, 1782-1854 ("What is the heart of you, dear story?", candy-factory and Club-Story-bouncer images, the worked tabulation of the eleven pre-contest pages)
    - paraphrase: name the central event the rest of the story should be serving (the heart), then walk through every other part asking what it does for that heart
    - situation: revising or critiquing a draft that feels long or off-center but you cannot say what specific section is failing against what reference point
    - outcome: → promoted to heart-of-the-story

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1924-1938 (side characters as "an ascending ladder of credibility" during the contest; the texting-friends-from-the-opera analogy)
    - paraphrase: when the central event of a story cannot be directly experienced by the reader (a song, a sermon, a dance), set up multiple side characters with established and differing credibilities so their graded reactions adjudicate the event for the reader
    - situation: drafting or revising a scene whose central event is unwitnessable on the page
    - outcome: → promoted to panel-of-judges

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 2002-2038 (the "holding up against" exercise; the two-trees painting analogy; the demonstration on the ravine and on the rooks/crows/sparrows)
    - paraphrase: take an apparently static element (a setting, an image, a digression) and juxtapose it mentally with the heart of the story; the immediate non-articulate response (relation found / not found) is the data, and articulation of the relation surfaces structural patterns (binaries, foreshadowed contrasts) the rest of the story is also organized by
    - situation: noticing an apparently decorative element that you suspect is structurally loaded but cannot articulate
    - outcome: → promoted to holding-up-against-the-heart

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 2064-2130 (wrist-meter / 1000 energy units; Olympic-sprinter-becomes-shotputter; "Hemingway Mountain" vs. "Saunders Mountain"; the autobiographical Seussian-poems-and-cartoons moment)
    - paraphrase: judge your own writing voice by the energy it generates in readers, not by whether it is the voice of the writer you wanted to be; when the energetic voice turns out to be a smaller, embarrassing one, commit to it
    - situation: a writer producing technically careful work in an aspired-to mode that elicits "interesting" rather than "alive" reactions
    - outcome: → promoted to energy-not-aspiration

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1704-1712 (A vs. B contest needs the contestants to "stand for something" so the outcome is meaningful)
    - paraphrase: in a story built on a contest of skills, A and B must each represent something distinct so the outcome can carry meaning
    - situation: drafting or revising a contest-shaped story where the outcome currently feels arbitrary
    - outcome: → folded into increasing-specification (this is increasing-specification applied at the level of contest stakes; the underlying move is the same — make each contestant a particular person who stands for something so action becomes meaningful — and Ch 6 sharpens the trigger to "your contest outcome feels arbitrary because A and B do not yet stand for distinct things")

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1730-1736 (reading fiction as "a series of establishings, stabilizations, and alterations")
    - paraphrase: every reading experience is a sequence of establishings ("the dog is sleeping"), stabilizations ("he is sleeping deeply"), and alterations ("he woke up")
    - situation: any close reading
    - outcome: → folded into page-break-diagnostic (this is the same beat-tracking the three-question protocol surfaces, restated in a different vocabulary; no new procedural content)

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: line 1748 ("specificity makes character")
    - paraphrase: a single specific way of doing the thing makes the character a particular person who stands for something
    - situation: drafting a character who currently feels generic
    - outcome: → folded into increasing-specification (this is the principle that skill operationalizes; the contest-specific application is captured by the fold above)

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1944-1946 (the "cut the story by 20% then 10% more" classroom assignment)
    - paraphrase: photocopy a published story and cut it down to a contemporary pace until you start cutting into the bone; learn touch by trimming someone else's work
    - situation: a writer who needs to develop the cutting instinct
    - outcome: → dropped because this is a teaching exercise, not a procedure with an observable signal or a recognizable failure mode that distinguishes good cutting from bad; the underlying ability ("touch") is named but not operationalized; Saunders himself frames it as a recommendation rather than a method (the deeper work of "what cuts" is captured by cornfeld-principle and take-responsibility-for-every-element). Note: Appendix A (Ch 24) is an actual cutting exercise and may surface a procedural skill on its own terms.

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 2140-2146 ("the blessing an artist gives the final product is his way of saying that he approves of everything within it"; pausing in the doorway, seeing nothing more to change)
    - paraphrase: the artist's final approval comes by letting the work stand and sending it out; you stop tinkering when nothing in the room asks to be changed
    - situation: late-stage revision when you suspect the work is done but keep adjusting
    - outcome: → folded into take-responsibility-for-every-element (the disposition of "approving everything within it" is the disposition that skill operationalizes; the "letting it stand" stopping rule is its terminal condition)

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - location: lines 1690 ("the Hollywood version" of "The Singers": "Two men have a singing contest in a Russian pub. One wins, one loses.")
    - paraphrase: brief restatement of hollywood-version applied to "The Singers"
    - situation: any teaching of the hollywood-version move
    - outcome: → folded into hollywood-version (a second worked instance of the same move; no new procedural content)

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2199-2203 (P/N meter on the forehead, instantaneous fix at every needle-drop, lather/rinse/repeat across hundreds of drafts), 2213-2217 (block-level "undeniability"; blocks start telling you their order), 2229-2237 (felt-not-decided; "intuition plus iteration"; "given infinite time, anything can happen"), 2247-2253 (apartment redecoration metaphor: hundreds of versions of you contributing one cut/swap per day), 2261-2267 (seed crystal; "overturning the tyranny of the first draft"; you don't need an idea, just a sentence)
    - paraphrase: revise by repeatedly reading the draft fresh as a first-time reader would, watching for an instinctive negative reaction at the line level, making the small fix that comes to mind, then doing it again, hundreds or thousands of times; the story shapes itself by accreted micro-decisions rather than top-down planning
    - situation: a writer revising a draft who keeps trying to plan the story's meaning, structure, or theme top-down, or who is paralyzed because the first draft is not good enough to start work on
    - outcome: → promoted to iterative-preference-revision

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2291-2303 (the Jane sentence reduced to "Jane" by asking why each element is needed), 2313-2335 (the Jim/Sara cut, removing what is contained in the action of dropping the keys; "the latter version has more respect for you, the reader, built into it"), 2337-2345 (story as frank conversation between equals; the writer imagines the reader as intelligent and worldly)
    - paraphrase: when revising, cut anything the reader can supply for themselves from what is already on the page; assume an intelligent reader and remove the parts that explain what the action or context already conveys
    - situation: revising prose that explains, narrates emotional reaction, or restates what an action already shows; the passage feels belabored even though no individual sentence is wrong
    - outcome: → promoted to respect-the-reader-cut

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2269-2281 ("Bob was an asshole" iteratively specified into "Bob snapped impatiently at the young barista, who reminded him of his dead wife..."; the unintended moral-ethical effect of specification)
    - paraphrase: when a flat or generic statement appears in your prose, revise it through successive rounds of "why" until the flat statement becomes a particular human moment; the moral richness emerges as a side effect of the specification, not as the goal
    - situation: revising a sentence that states a verdict on a character (he was an asshole, she was sad, they were happy) instead of rendering the moment that produced the verdict
    - outcome: → folded into increasing-specification (the move is the same — ask why, add a fact that rules out the generic version, repeat — applied to a single sentence rather than to a character introduction; Ch 7 supplies the moral-ethical side-effect framing and the prose-line worked example)

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2229, 2231-2233 ("when I'm writing well, there's almost no intellectual/analytical thinking going on"; the relief of not having to decide; willing to make playful changes at the line level knowing the next read offers a chance to revert)
    - paraphrase: a stance of trusting felt impulse rather than analysis during revision; you don't have to commit to a change because the next pass can undo it
    - situation: writers who feel paralyzed by every revision decision because they treat each change as final
    - outcome: → folded into iterative-preference-revision (this is the disposition that makes the iterative method work; the skill operationalizes it via "make the change now, knowing the next pass can revert")

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - location: lines 2183-2189 (Stan and the model railroad: hobo posture, turning the plastic woman, "all art begins in that instant of intuitive preference")
    - paraphrase: art begins in pre-articulate preference, the small "yes" that occurs before language; trust the impulse before trying to explain it
    - situation: any moment of artistic adjustment
    - outcome: → folded into iterative-preference-revision (the Stan story is the chapter's opening illustration of the same move the skill operationalizes; the "instant of intuitive preference" is the felt event the P/N meter trains you to notice)

- Chapter 8: The Darling (Chekhov source story)
    - location: lines 2351-2542 (entire chapter)
    - paraphrase: no candidates. The chapter is Chekhov's story as Saunders presents it, with no Saunders commentary. Visible structural features include the four-attachment pattern (papa and aunt and French teacher in childhood, then Kukin the theater manager, then Pustovalov the lumberyard manager, then Smirnin the veterinary, then finally the boy Sasha), the repeated mechanism by which Olenka takes on each partner's vocabulary and opinions as her own, the deflated middle stretch in which she has no one and consequently no opinions at all, the loud structural rhyme between the late-night telegram-knock that announces Kukin's death and the late-night knock that turns out to be the veterinary returning from the club at the end, and the way the closing Sasha attachment is set apart from the prior three by the narrator's explicit comment that none of her former attachments was as deep. Each is a teachable feature in principle, but the procedural form (action, observable signal, named failure mode) cannot be articulated honestly from the story alone without anticipating Chapter 9's commentary, which is out of scope for this pass.
    - situation: not applicable
    - outcome: → none promoted; the story is data the next chapter (titled "A Pattern Story") will use to teach moves about repetition-as-pattern, identity through relationship, and how a story differentiates a final repetition from earlier ones

